Ailanthus excelsa

    Authority   Roxb.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Sapindales:Simaroubaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 2944

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A medium-sized, deciduous tree reaching 18-25 m in
   height, with a straight trunk up to 60-80 cm in diameter. USES The wood
   is used as firewood and for boxes, crates, fishing floats, toys, tool
   handles, and matches. Bark and leaves have medicinal properties and the
   tree can provide fodder and shelter. Mentioned as a possible
   agroforestry species. KILLING T Can withstand considerable frosts.
   GROWING PERIOD Fast-growing perennial. In India it flowers in
   February-March, new leaves appear in March-April, fruits ripen in
   May-June, and the leaves are shed during the cold season. COMMON NAMES
   Maharukh, Ganges, Ardusi, Ardu, Arduso, Aduso, Alvo, Bhutrongo,
   Bhutrakho, Maharuka, Mahanium, Pir nim, Horanim aaruk, Maruf, Arua,
   Mahanim, Limbado, Ajau, Peetherai, Helbeva, Doddamara, Peenari, Matii
   pongilyam, Varul, Gormi-kawat, Mahalimbo, Madala, Pimaram, Pinari,
   Peru, Perumaram, Periamaram, Pedda manu, Peeda, Pey, Pedu, Pee
   vepachettu, Mothoaradusa, Coromandel ailanto. FURTHER INF Maharukh can
   in the tropics be found at elevations up to about 900 m. It is adapted
   to a relative humidity of 40-80% in the winter and 60-90% in the
   summer. The species is indigenous to India. It is often found in rows
   at the edges of farms or streams. Survivability is poor if the trees
   are not sufficiently watered during the first and seccond years of
   establishment. It is said to be easily broken by wind.

   Sources
